sec.p:
Aerodynamic drag is a phenomenon known from daily life, may it be the head wind experienced on a bicycle or the tail wind that accelerates a sailing boat: whenever there is a difference in velocity between an object and the surrounding gas, the drag force acts towards eliminating the velocity difference. The same principles apply to solids in circumstellar disks that are dynamically coupled to the gas via drag forces. However in most regions of the disk, the drag stems not from the flow around the object as we experience it. Instead, most dust grains are smaller than the mean free path of the gas molecules and they rather feel drag by being bombarded by gas molecules slightly faster from the direction of the flow than behind it, effectively a pressure force. This drag force is called Epstein drag (in contrast to the better known Stokes drag, which can become relevant in the denser inner regions of disks). The Epstein drag force is expressed as (Weidenschilling 1977a) 1FEp=−4π3ρga2Δwvth,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
