The case of turbulent velocities is much more complicated: particle velocities are affected by turbulent eddies through which they move. Turbulent eddies of different sizes cause partial alignment of particle trajectories on short distances or induce random kicks, depending on the eddy turnover time, the particle stopping time, and the time it takes the particle to cross the eddy. The classical picture was introduced by Völk et al. (1980) and allowed Ormel and Cuzzi (2007) to derive closed form expressions that are currently widely used. Pan and Padoan (2010), Pan et al. (2014) and following papers in this series criticized this picture, emphasizing the importance of the particle separation prior to a collision in determining the degree of correlation between particle velocities induced by turbulent eddies of different sizes. Their results deviate somewhat from the results of Ormel and Cuzzi (2007) (predicting a maximum velocity by about a factor of two lower) and they additionally allow the calculation of the distribution of collision velocities. In the following examples, we will use approximations to the velocities derived by Ormel and Cuzzi (2007) for simplicity. In this framework, the collision speed depends on the particle sizes of both particles and on the largest and smallest eddy turn-over times. For equal sized particles with stopping times larger than the smallest eddy turn-over times, the velocities can be approximated by 22Δvturb≃3αSt+St−1cs,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
