This picture of growth, drift, and fragmentation may be quite simplistic, but it was found to match well the behavior seen in numerical simulations (see Birnstiel et al. 2012b), which incorporate many more details. A similar behavior, at least in the outer disk was also found in cases where the porosity of the grains was allowed to change: Okuzumi et al. (2012) considered icy grains and assumed that they do not fragment.4 In their simulations, particles grow in a fractal way reaching very low filling factors (∼10−5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
